## SECTION 5 — AUDIENCE INTELLIGENCE

**Who they are:**
Mixed expertise. Primarily women 18–40 who have tried nail colour recommendations that didn't work — they picked a shade they saw on Pinterest or Instagram, it looked wrong on their hands, and they now want to understand why. Significant South Asian, olive, and deep skin presence who feel underserved by mainstream beauty guides. Fair-skin readers are also present but better-served elsewhere, so tone sections must still be strong enough to validate them.

**What they want from this post:**
A practical decision-making framework they can use today — not aspirational inspiration, not a product roundup. They want to understand undertone, identify their own, and walk away knowing exactly which colour families will work and which will disappoint. They also want validation that the colours they've tried and failed weren't mistakes of taste, but mismatches of method.

**What frustrates them:**
- Shade lists with no reasoning. "Coral looks great on medium skin" tells them nothing they don't already know.
- Fair-skin-centric content that treats other tones as footnotes.
- "Universal" recommendations that don't actually work on their tone.
- Conflating skin tone (surface depth) with undertone (temperature). Most guides never clarify this.
- Articles that make them scroll through 4,000 words of product links to find one useful sentence.

**Top 5 pain points:**
1. Can't find their undertone confidently — vein test feels ambiguous, no guidance on cross-checking
2. Nude polish always looks wrong — either too pink, too grey, or invisibly washed out
3. Trending colours consistently don't translate to their skin tone the way they did on the editor's hand
4. Olive and medium-dark skin tones feel invisible in most guides
5. They know they want something "flattering" but have no logic to use at the salon when facing a wall of colours

